// C2: Acting Components
instance SysMLStateMachineEngine : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Active processing component implementing SysML state machines for behavioral modeling and decision support via simulation outputs"
]

instance MontiArcAutomataProcessor : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Active software component executing MontiArc automata for behavioral consistency checks and decision-making processes"
]

instance SimulationExecutionEngine : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "General-purpose execution engine (C++/Java) running simulation outputs from MathWorks Simulink for real-time/batch analytics"
]

// C3: Physical sensing components
instance PhysicalSystemInterface : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Interface layer aggregating contextual data traces from physical systems via digital shadows"
]

instance SensorDataAggregator : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Component responsible for collecting and preprocessing contextual data traces from physical objects"
]

instance StakeholderModelInterface : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Interface capturing stakeholder-aligned models (SysML IBDs) for behavioral validation and decision support"
]

instance ContextualDataTraces : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom PhysicalSystemInterface
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance BehavioralSimulationOutputs : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom SimulationExecutionEngine
]

instance ADLValidationResults : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MontiArcAutomataProcessor
]

instance StakeholderModelData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom StakeholderModelInterface
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance SysMLStateMachineModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Behavioral model implemented via SysML state machines (v1.7) capturing system dynamics and decision-making processes"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulationExecutionEngine
]

instance MontiArcAutomataModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Behavioral model defined using MontiArc automata for consistency checks and decision validation"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MontiArcAutomataProcessor
]

instance SimulationEnvironmentModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simulation environment model created in MathWorks Simulink for executing behavioral simulations"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulationExecutionEngine
]

instance ADLArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Architecture description model (AADL/MontiArc) defining system components, interfaces, and interconnections"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MontiArcAutomataProcessor
]

instance StakeholderRequirementsModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Requirements and functional/logical architecture model (SysML IBDs) aligning with stakeholder perspectives"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo StakeholderModelInterface
]

instance DigitalShadowDataStore : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Centralized storage of contextual data traces aggregated from physical systems for digital shadow purposes"
    DTDFVocab:fromData ContextualDataTraces
]

instance SimulationResultsDatabase : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Database storing simulation outputs (MathWorks Simulink) for analytics and decision support"
    DTDFVocab:fromData BehavioralSimulationOutputs
]

instance ValidationMetricsDatabase : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Database containing ADL validation results (AADL/MontiArc) for behavioral consistency checks"
    DTDFVocab:fromData ADLValidationResults
]

instance StakeholderModelRepository : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Repository of stakeholder-aligned models (SysML IBDs) for decision-making processes"
    DTDFVocab:fromData StakeholderModelData
]

// C11: Enablers
instance MBSEToolIntegration : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Integration framework enabling heterogeneous MBSE toolchains (SysML, AADL, MontiArc, Simulink) for unified modeling"
]

instance BehavioralModelingFramework : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Framework supporting state machines (SysML) and automata (MontiArc) for behavioral modeling and validation"
]

instance SimulationEngineIntegration : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Integration layer connecting simulation engines (Simulink) with behavioral models and analytics"
]

instance ADLValidationFramework : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Architecture description language validation framework (AADL/MontiArc) for behavioral consistency checks"
]

instance StakeholderAlignmentFramework : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Framework ensuring alignment between stakeholder perspectives and system models (SysML IBDs)"
]

// C6: Services
instance SimulationAnalyticsService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing real-time/batch analytics on simulation outputs (Simulink) for decision support"
    DTDFVocab:enables SimulationEngineIntegration
    DTDFVocab:provides SimulationResultsDatabase
]

instance StateMachineValidationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service validating behavioral models using SysML state machines for consistency checks"
    DTDFVocab:enables BehavioralModelingFramework
    DTDFVocab:provides ValidationMetricsDatabase
]

instance ValidationConsistencyService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service ensuring ADL-based validation compliance (AADL/MontiArc) for behavioral models"
    DTDFVocab:enables ADLValidationFramework
    DTDFVocab:provides ValidationMetricsDatabase
]

instance DecisionSupportService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing stakeholder-aligned decision support based on model alignment and behavioral validation"
    DTDFVocab:enables StakeholderAlignmentFramework
    DTDFVocab:provides StakeholderModelRepository
]

instance DigitalShadowAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service aggregating and abstracting contextual data traces from physical systems for digital shadow purposes"
    DTDFVocab:enables MBSEToolIntegration
    DTDFVocab:provides ContextualDataTraces
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance InsightsFromSimulationResults : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Behavioral insights generated from simulation outputs (Simulink) for functional/logical validation"
]

instance BehavioralConsistencyChecks : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Results from state machine/automata validation ensuring behavioral consistency between models"
]

instance ValidationRigorMetrics : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Metrics quantifying validation rigor (simulation accuracy, ADL compliance) for confidence assessment"
]

instance DecisionRecommendations : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Decision-making outputs informed by stakeholder-aligned models and behavioral consistency checks"
]

instance ContextualDataTracesAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automatic data aggregation and abstraction of physical system context for digital shadow representation"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance SimulationExecutionAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Execution of behavioral models (C++/Java) in simulation environments (Simulink) for analytics"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance BehavioralValidationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Validation of behavioral models through state machines/automata (MontiArc) and ADL compliance checks"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance DecisionMakingProcess : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Process of generating decision recommendations based on stakeholder models and behavioral consistency"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "A Digital Twin system in this context does not explicitly define synchronization frequencies, latency requirements, or temporal granularity for twinning. However, the distinction between **Digital Shadows** and **Digital Twins** implies that while a **Digital Shadow** operates as a **passive, one-way data flow** (e.g., aggregating contextual data traces with abstraction for a specific purpose), a **Digital Twin** would inherently require **active components** to interpret and process data in real-time or near-real-time. This suggests that the **twinning time scale** for a Digital Twin would involve **frequent, bidirectional synchronization** (e.g., sub-second to real-time updates) to enable autonomous operations and data-driven decision-making. The provided documents do not specify exact time scales or synchronization protocols, but the emphasis on **active components** (e.g., for behavior modeling via tools like **MathWorks Simulink** or state machines in **SysML**) implies a need for **high-frequency, tightly coupled temporal alignment** between physical and digital systems to support real-time coordination and predictive capabilities. If not explicitly defined, the system’s temporal granularity would depend on the **behavioral modeling tools** (e.g., state machines, automata) used to describe system dynamics, which may require **discrete-event simulation** or **continuous-time modeling** approaches. Thus, while no exact values are provided, the **twinning time scale** is implied to be **high-frequency and tightly synchronized** to enable autonomous DT operations and real-time decision-making, with potential use of **MBSE methodologies** (e.g., SysML, MontiArc) for modeling temporal dependencies across abstraction layers."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The **Digital Twin constellation** in this context is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents, but the **Digital Shadow** reference model (Fig. 1) and the distinction between **passive shadows** and **active twins** imply a **highly orchestrated system architecture**. A Digital Twin constellation would likely involve:
   - **Architecture patterns** derived from **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **MontiArc** or **SysML IBDs**, which define **component composition, interconnections, and behavior** (e.g., via state machines or automata).
   - **Component integration** leveraging **model-based systems engineering (MBSE)** methodologies (e.g., **RFLP, OOSEM, SMArDT**) to manage **heterogeneous stakeholders’ perspectives** and **multi-layered abstractions** (requirements → functional → logical → technical layers).
   - **Resource management** would be handled via **simulation tools** (e.g., **MathWorks Simulink**) or **code in general-purpose languages** (e.g., **C++, Java**) to ensure real-time synchronization and autonomy.
   - **System-wide coordination mechanisms** would rely on **bidirectional data flows** (unlike passive shadows) and **active components** (e.g., interpreters, decision engines) to enable **closed-loop control** and **predictive capabilities**.
   The documents suggest that the **Digital Twin constellation** would be **centralized or distributed**, with coordination governed by **ADLs and MBSE frameworks**, but no specific constellation patterns (e.g., **peer-to-peer, star topology**) or inter-twin protocols are detailed. The **lack of explicit mention** implies a **highly flexible, model-driven orchestration** where twins are dynamically integrated via **ADLs and simulation tools** to support **autonomous, real-time operations**."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
    A Digital Twin (DT) lifecycle in the described context is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, spanning multiple abstraction levels (requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers). The lifecycle stages are implicitly implied by the **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics)**, **OOSEM**, **SPES**, or **SMArDT** frameworks, which govern the evolution of DTs from conceptual design to operational deployment.

    **Key Phases and Representations:**
    - **Requirements Phase:** Defined via **SysML** or **ADLs** (e.g., AADL, MontiArc) to capture functional and structural constraints.
    - **Functional/Logical Architecture:** Described using **component & connector perspectives** (e.g., ACME, MontiArc Automaton) with behavior modeled via **state machines** (SysML v1.7) or **simulation tools** (e.g., MathWorks Simulink).
    - **Product/Technical Layer:** Finalized with **code** (e.g., C++, Java) or simulation outputs, integrating heterogeneous tools (e.g., AADL, MontiArc) for interoperability.

    **Transition Management:** Transitions between phases rely on **ABSE (Architecture Description Languages)** and **simulation integration** (e.g., Simulink) to validate behavior across abstraction layers. **Version control** (implicitly implied by MBSE tool chains) ensures traceability, while **lifecycle governance** is supported by structured methodologies (RFLP/SPES) ensuring alignment with stakeholder perspectives.

    **Note:** The document does not explicitly enumerate stages but implies a **multi-layered, iterative lifecycle** driven by MBSE and ADLs, with **digital shadows** (passive data flows) as a foundational layer for DT evolution.
  "
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
  **Fidelity and validity** in this Digital Twin system are implicitly addressed through:
  - **Model validation/verification**: Enforced via **MBSE’s layered abstraction** (requirements → architecture → simulation), where **ADLs (e.g., SysML, AADL)** and **simulation tools (e.g., Simulink)** ensure consistency across components and behaviors.
  - **Uncertainty quantification**: Not explicitly quantified; instead, reliance on **active software components** (for digital shadows) and **stakeholder-integrated modeling** (e.g., heterogeneous perspectives) implicitly manages errors.
  - **Error detection/correction**: Implicit in **ADLs’ behavioral modeling** (e.g., state machines) and **simulation validation loops**, though no formal mechanisms (e.g., statistical methods, calibration) are detailed.
  - **Quality assurance**: Embedded in **MBSE’s methodological rigor** (e.g., RFLP, OOSEM), ensuring traceability and alignment across abstraction layers. No explicit auditing or certification standards are referenced.

  **No explicit validation protocols** (e.g., ISO/IEC 25010) or error bounds are provided.
  "
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "
  **Network Infrastructure for Digital Twins:**
  The documents do not explicitly detail technical network infrastructure for Digital Twins (DTs) or Digital Shadows. However, the context implies reliance on:
  - **Communication Protocols**: Likely leverages **industry-standard protocols** (e.g., OPC UA, MQTT, or custom ADL-based messaging) for interoperability between physical components and digital models, though specifics are absent.
  - **Network Topology**: Assumes a **hierarchical or distributed architecture** (e.g., cloud-edge-on-premise) to support multi-level abstraction (requirements → technical layers) as per MBSE methodologies (e.g., RFLP, OOSEM).
  - **Bandwidth/Latency**: Not quantified, but critical for real-time synchronization between physical and digital states (e.g., in manufacturing twins).
  - **Reliability/Redundancy**: Implied by the passive nature of Digital Shadows (no autonomous correction mechanisms), but no redundancy protocols (e.g., failover clusters) or fault-tolerant designs are described.
  - **Security Protocols**: Not addressed; potential gaps in authentication (e.g., TLS for data integrity) or encryption (e.g., field-level security for sensor data) are not mentioned.
  **Note**: The Digital Shadow’s passive role (one-way flow) suggests minimal active network requirements, but no technical specifics are provided.
 "
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "
  **Deployment Infrastructure for Digital Twins:**
  The documents outline **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** frameworks (e.g., SysML, ADLs) but do not specify hosting platforms (cloud/edge/on-premise). However, inferred requirements include:
  - **Hosting Platforms**: Likely supports **cloud-based deployment** (e.g., AWS, Azure) for scalability, given the mention of heterogeneous stakeholders and multi-abstraction layers (e.g., requirements → technical layers).
  - **Computational/Storage Requirements**: Implies **high-performance computing (HPC)** for simulating complex systems (e.g., state machines, automata) and storing aggregated data traces. No specific benchmarks (e.g., CPU cores, RAM) are provided.
  - **Scalability Mechanisms**: Enabled by **modular ADLs** (e.g., MontiArc, SysML IBDs) that decompose systems into composable components, allowing horizontal scaling of digital models.
  - **Deployment Models**: Supports **infrastructure-as-code (IaC)** or containerized deployments (e.g., Docker/Kubernetes) to manage heterogeneous tools (e.g., Simulink, C++ code).
  - **Availability/Reliability Assurance**: Critical for real-time DTs, but no SLAs (e.g., 99.9% uptime) or redundancy strategies (e.g., multi-AZ cloud deployments) are detailed.
  **Note**: The focus on **MBSE methodologies** (e.g., RFLP, SMArDT) suggests a **hybrid deployment** (cloud-edge) to balance computational demands and latency-sensitive operations, though specifics are absent.
  "
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "
    **Standards Compliance:**
    - **Modeling Languages:** Adherence to **SysML** (for requirements/behavioral modeling) and **Architecture Description Languages (ADLs)** (e.g., AADL, MontiArc, ACME).
    - **Industry Standards:** Implicitly referenced via **MBSE methodologies** (RFLP, OOSEM) and **simulation tools** (MathWorks Simulink), though no explicit standards are named.
    - **Certification Requirements:** Not detailed; however, **ADL compliance** (e.g., AADL) may imply certification via vendor frameworks (e.g., AADL Toolkit).
    - **Compliance Frameworks:** **Model integration** (e.g., SysML + Simulink) suggests adherence to **industry-specific MBSE frameworks** (e.g., DO-178C for aerospace).
    - **Interoperability Standards:** **Heterogeneous tool integration** (e.g., SysML + C++/Java) implies compliance with **open standards** (e.g., OMG SysML, IEC 61499 for control systems).

    **Note:** The document does not specify explicit certification bodies or interoperability protocols but highlights **ADL/SysML-centric standardization** and **toolchain compatibility**.
  "
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system leverages the **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** framework, as defined by the **Plattform Industrie 4.0** (2019), to ensure robust security and safety compliance. The AAS integrates **cybersecurity protocols** through standardized interfaces for secure data exchange, particularly within the **RAMI 4.0** architecture (DIN/IEC 2016), which categorizes system layers (Physical, Technical, Business, and Organizational) to enforce hierarchical access controls and threat mitigation.

Key technical measures include:
- **Authentication and Access Control**: Enforced via **semantic asset administration shell (SAAS)** principles (Bader & Maleshkova, 2019), ensuring role-based permissions and **conformance relations** (Konersmann et al., 2024) for validating structural integrity of digital representations.
- **Threat Mitigation**: The system employs **model-driven engineering (MDE)** (Heithoff et al., 2025) to preemptively address cyber risks by embedding fail-safe mechanisms in the **Digital Shadow** layer (Heithoff et al., 2025), which mirrors real-time operational states across the automation pyramid (e.g., IoT, PLCs, and cloud platforms).
- **Safety-Critical Systems**: The **Functional Mockup Interface (FMI)** (Blochwitz et al., 2011) ensures tool-independent exchange of simulation models, critical for validating safety-critical behaviors in manufacturing Digital Twins (e.g., robotic arms like the **MABI Max-100** (MABI, 2025), which requires friction modeling for dynamic stability—Trinh et al., 2023).
- **Protocol Integration**: The system may utilize **MQTT** (Light, 2017) for lightweight, low-latency communication between IoT devices and the Digital Twin, though explicit privacy safeguards (e.g., end-to-end encryption) are not detailed in the provided documents.
- **Risk Assessment**: The **RAMI 4.0** framework inherently embeds risk assessment by defining explicit layers for cyber-physical interaction, though no specific methodologies (e.g., ISO 27001 compliance) are referenced.
"
]